, United Kingdom","Utkinton, Cheshire, England":"Utkinton, Cheshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Swinnerton","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English: habitational name from Swynnerton in Staffordshire. The etymology of the placename is uncertain. It may derive from Old English <i>swille</i> ‘sloppy mess, swill’ + <i>ford</i> ‘ford’ + <i>tūn</i> ‘farmstead, estate’. Alternatively, the first element may be <i>swīn</i> ‘swine, hog’, <i>swān</i> ‘herdsman, peasant’, <i>swan</i> ‘swan’, or <i>sumor</i> ‘summer’."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Ellen","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Originally a variant of   Helen  , although now no longer associated with that name. Initial <i>H-</i> tended to be added and dropped rather capriciously, leading to many doublets (  compare for example  Esther   and   Hester  ). It is also sometimes used as a short form of   Eleanor  , to which, however, it is unrelated."],"variants":[{"name":"Eleanor","meanings":["From an Old French respelling of the Old Provençal name <i>Alienor</i>. This has sometimes been taken as a derivative of   Helen  , but it is more probably of Germanic derivation (the first element being <i>ali</i> ‘other, foreign’ the second is obscure). The name was introduced to England by  Eleanor of Aquitaine  (  1122–1204 ), who came from Aquitaine in south-west France to be the wife of  King Henry II . It was also borne by Eleanor of Provence, the wife of  Henry III , and Eleanor of Castile, wife of  Edward I ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Ellen Swinnerton was born about 1285, in Hilton, Staffordshire, England, United Kingdom, her father, Thomas Swinnerton, was 37 and her mother, Matilda Holland, was 32. She married Richard Dunn or Done about 1309. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1285–":"umbes 1285–Surnud","1275–1298":"1275–1298